long_desc.thetext:
There are existing OSLC clients and servers that implemented OSLC 1.0. When OSLC 2.0 was developed, these clients and servers updated to OSLC 2.0, but for backward compatibility, continued to support OSLC 1.0. OSLC 2.0 introduced the OSLC-Core-Version header to identify the OSLC version. Some clients and servers (e.g., RDNG and RTC) default to OSLC 1.0 because when it was implemented, the OSLC-Core-Version header did not exist.

In order to use clients and servers created with the Toolchain modeler and code generator with these applications, the services need to set the OSLC-Core-Version header to 2.0 in all HTTP responses.

Specifically:
1. in <app>Constants.java, add:
    public static final String OSLC_VERSION_V2 = "2.0";

2. in the *Service. java file (the file that implements the OSLC REST services)

2.1. for PUT, and DELETE, change:
return Response.ok().build();
to:
return Response.created(newResource.getAbout()).entity(aResource).header(CE4IoTConnectorConstants.HDR_OSLC_VERSION, CE4IoTConnectorConstants.OSLC_VERSION_V2).build();

2.2. for POST (create), change
return Response.created(newResource.getAbout()).entity(aResource).build();
to:
return Response.created(newResource.getAbout()).entity(aResource).header(CE4IoTConnectorConstants.HDR_OSLC_VERSION, CE4IoTConnectorConstants.OSLC_VERSION_V2).build();

2.3. for GET, add the following right before the resource is returned:
httpServletResponse.addHeader(CE4IoTConnectorConstants.HDR_OSLC_VERSION, CE4IoTConnectorConstants.OSLC_VERSION_V2);

If the resources have loops in the reference properties, Jena model helper will crash with the StackOverflowException. An IdentityHashMap shall be kept during the recursive traversal to prevent walking the loop references (but all loops will be preserved in the triplestore):

