I used the following code to prevent the same kind of an exception in the toString() method (credit: https://stackoverflow.com/a/11300376):

    private final static ThreadLocal<IdentityHashMap<Package, ?>> fToStringChecker = ThreadLocal
            .withInitial(IdentityHashMap::new);

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        final IdentityHashMap<Package, ?> identityHashMap = fToStringChecker.get();
        if(identityHashMap.containsKey(this)) {
            return "##recursive loop##";
        } else {
            identityHashMap.put(this, null);
            return MoreObjects.toStringHelper(this)
                    .add("isContainedInEquipment", isContainedInEquipment)
                    .add("isMovedBy", isMovedBy)
                    .add("volume", volume)
                    .toString();
        }
    }

Hi Jad,

To address this we have added following method in the delegatedUI.js file

method:

function escapeCSSAttack(url) {
    var out = "";
    for(var i=0; i<url.length; i++) {
        if(url[i] === '<') {
            out += '&amp;lt;';
        } else if(url[i] === '>') {
            out += '&amp;gt;';
        } else if(url[i] === "'") {
            out += '&amp;#39;';
        } else if(url[i] === '"') {
            out += '&amp;quot;';
        } else {
            out += url[i];
        }
    }
    return out;
}


changes in respondWithWindowName function:
line 136:
  var returnURL = escapeCSSAttack(window.name);

Thanks!

Hi Andrew and Jad,

Here is my solution:

function respondWithWindowName(/*string*/ response) {
	   var isValid = validateUrl(window.name);

	   if(isValid){
		   var returnURL = escapeCSSAttack(window.name);
		   window.name = response;
		   window.location.href = returnURL;
	   }
	   else{
		   console.error("Invalid URL: window.name");
		   return;
	   }
}

I am validating the window.name value and which suppose to be an URL.
So if it's a correct URL still it can have something malicious in it as path or query parameters so I will still encode it.
And if it's not a correct URL and just some malicious script, just throw a console error and break the execution.
validateUrl here is my own function which validates the URL against a RegEx.

I tried and tested all these changes and also scanned though the IBM Web Scan.

Let me know if you agree with this. And I am sorry for delay in response but I am not receiving any notifications for comments here.

Right now, OSLC4J assumes a response that contains multiple resources is an OSLC query response. Often you want to have more than one resource in a response that is not a query. This is common with TRS and LDP.

Here is an example from the OSLC-CM 3.0 attachments draft spec [1]. This is difficult to model today using OSLC4J since the ChangeRequest, the top-level resource, does not have a property pointing to the ldp:Container.

@prefix oslc_cm: <http://open-services.net/ns/cm#> .
@prefix ldp: <http://w3.org/ns/ldp#> .

<>
   a oslc_cm:ChangeRequest ;
   oslc_cm:attachment
      <attachments/1>,
      <attachments/2> .

<attachments>
   a ldp:Container;
   ldp:membershipPredicate oslc_cm:attachment;
   ldp:membershipSubject <.>.

[1] http://open-services.net/wiki/change-management/Attachments-for-Change-Requests/

