As an overall description, I have JAX-RS methods that accept and produce content in different media types.

To exaggerate the problem for the purposes of bug reporting, let's say I have a method like this:

    @POST
    @Consumes("application/rdf+xml")
    @Produces("application/json")
    @Path("pr")
    public Response setServiceProviderAsRdfXml2(@Context UriInfo ctx, ServiceProvider sp) {
        ResponseBuilder respBuilder = Response.ok();
        Response response = respBuilder.entity(sp).type("application/json").build();
        return response;
    }

----

See the transcript of a successful HTTP session (headers and bodies) in oslc4j-post-as-xml-retrieve-as-json.txt.

Then we deliberately break the input XML content and reissue the exact same request, the resulting oslc:Error payload comes back with in application/rdf+xml format, as one can see in oslc4j-post-as-xml-retrieve-as-json-failure.txt

The generated Application.java class includes code such as
    RESOURCE_CLASSES.add(Requirement.class);
    RESOURCE_CLASSES.add(Mission.class);

This produces warnings such as

WARN org.apache.wink.server.internal.application.ApplicationProcessor - The sandbox.resources.Mission class is neither a resource nor a provider. The runtime is ignoring this class. It was returned from a javax.ws.rs.core.Application subclass. Add either a @javax.ws.rs.Path or a @javax.ws.rs.core.Provider annotation to the class.

