Here's my proposal. I believe we just need to clarify to the developer what the options are.

Current code:
-------------
private static final String DEFAULT_BASE = "http://localhost:8080";
private static final String PROPERTY_BASE = servletContextParameterName("baseurl");

public void contextInitialized(final ServletContextEvent servletContextEvent) {
   ....
   String baseUrl = generateBasePath(servletContextEvent);
   ....
}


Proposal code:
--------------
//To control the baseURL for all your resources, modify the values of these variables early in the method contextInitialized().
private static String DEFAULT_BASE = "http://localhost:8080";
private static String PROPERTY_BASE = servletContextParameterName("baseurl");

public void contextInitialized(final ServletContextEvent servletContextEvent) {
    // Start of user code contextInitialized_init
    //TODO: override the default values of DEFAULT_BASE, PROPERTY_BASE and servletName. You have the following options:
    //1. Control the baseURL through the web.xml file, by setting PROPERTY_BASE to match your parameter in the web.xml file.
    //2. control the baseURL directly in this class, by (a) setting DEFAULT_BASE to match your desired value and (b) setting PROPERTY_BASE = null;

    //DEFAULT_BASE = "Your_Desired_Default_base";
    //Property_BASE = "Your_Desired_Property_base";
    // End of user code

    ....
}

Notes:
------
* That is, DEFAULT_BASE & PROPERTY_BASE are no "final".
* We need to find better names than DEFAULT_BASE & PROPERTY_BASE.
* Should they no longer be static variables then, so that they can be defined within the contextInitialized method (where they are actually used)
* While at it, I think we can similarly, improve the instructions on how the serveletName can be controlled. The variable "servletName".

1.
Adding protected code in the method generateBasePath() is surely possible, but it might be hard for developer to notice.

Can we instead focus the use of protected user code to within the contextInitialized() method?
so, how about wrapping the call to generateBasePath() with protected code.

public void contextInitialized(final ServletContextEvent servletContextEvent) {
   ....
    // Start of user code contextInitialized_init
    String baseUrl = generateBasePath(servletContextEvent);
    // End of user code

}

2.
And, btw, ultimatly, It is the call OSLC4JUtils.setPublicURI(baseUrl) that is of relevance.
The method setPublicURI is what counts, and that can be set anytime/anywhere.

3. Given point 3 above, you know you can simply call OSLC4JUtils.setPublicURI(...) from xManager.contextInitializeServletListener().
This way, the only code htat needs to be changed is within the Manager class.

