I am not sure if we need to fix this problem, but here's the analysis.

Analysing the code
-------------------

You defined a value property on an OSLC resource as:
    private Link value = new Link();


You also set its annotations as:
    @OslcName("value")
    @OslcPropertyDefinition(PpConstants.PLANNING_NAMSPACE + "value")
    @OslcOccurs(Occurs.ExactlyOne)
    @OslcValueType(ValueType.LocalResource)
    @OslcReadOnly(false)
    public Link getValue()
    {
        return value;
    }

Being a LocalResource, the ResourceShapeFactory tries to create a shape out of the property's type. Since Link extends AbstractReifiedResource<URI>, the ResourceShapeFactory tries to create a shape out of the base class (ie URI).
Now since the URI has no OSLC-shape annotations, you get an exception.

Solution: Set the type of the property to something with annotations.
In a way, it is strange to have a LocalResource whose value is a URI/Link.

Problems in the generated code
------------------------------

Being generated code, the real problem lies in the fact that you defined a property to have a valueType as LocalResource, yet did not set its Range.

Now, the generator defaults to Link, if no range is defined. This seems obviously bad. What should it default to? AbstractResource?

A couple of property names are incorrect in the javadoc comments in OSLC4JUtils.

The correct property names are:

OSLC4J_PUBLIC_URI              = "org.eclipse.lyo.oslc4j.publicURI";
OSLC4J_DISABLE_HOST_RESOLUTION = "org.eclipse.lyo.oslc4j.disableHostResolution";

Some env try to connect using OSLC Client, but the Secure Socket Protocol is selected based on a predefined array : {"TLS","SSL","SSL_TLS"};

We need a way for clients to select the proper Secure Socket Protocol

PLS assign it to me.

This should not be happening:

public ClientResponse getResource(String url) throws IOException,
			OAuthException, URISyntaxException

The login() method of the anymous Application class created in AbstractAdapterCredentialsFilter.init() throws an AuthenticationException based on a catched exception:

catch (Exception e) {
    throw new AuthenticationException(e.getCause().getMessage(), e);
}

This code assumes a cause is always available on the catched exception. However if for some reason the exception has no cause (i.e. this is a root exception, like a NullPointerException of IllegalArgumentException), the code will fail with a NullPointerException, as getCause() returns null, which makes harder to track down the original problem.

Each Resource contains the following method that returns an instance of its resource shape.


    public static ResourceShape createResourceShape() throws OslcCoreApplicationException, URISyntaxException {
        return ResourceShapeFactory.createResourceShape(OSLC4JUtils.getPublicURI(),
        OslcConstants.PATH_RESOURCE_SHAPES,
        TestingToolConstants.PATH_TESTCASE,
        TestCase.class);
    }


This produces a shape with an about
http://localhost:8080/iotp/resourceShapes/testCase
But it ought to be
http://localhost:8080/iotp/services/resourceShapes/testCase

