public class XMLLiteralTester {

	/**
	 * @param args
	 */
	public static void main(String[] args) {

		Model model = ModelFactory.createDefaultModel();
		InputStream in = FileManager.get().open( "data.rdf" );
		model.read(in, null);
		InfModel infModel = ModelFactory.createRDFSModel(model);

		ValidityReport report = infModel.validate();
		if (report.isClean())
		{
			System.out.println("The model is good");
		}
		else
		{
			System.out.println("Bad model");

                }
	}
}

and the ValidityReport is clean.

Let me know if you agree or think this is still incorrect.

I still think this is incorrect. Please consider that in your last example you change:

1. <dcterms:title> 1 &lt; 2 </dcterms:title>
to
2. <dcterms:title rdf:parseType="Literal"> 1 &lt; 2 </dcterms:title>

which is something quite different. #1 tell us to set dcterms:title with the value " 1 < 2 ". It was written as " 1 &lt; 2 " because it is transmitted in XML so it will be unquoted to " 1 < 2 ".

In #2 I say dcterms:title has value " 1 &lt; 2 " literally. So it won't be unquoted.
To show you the difference I get following file:
<rdf:RDF
   xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#"
   xmlns:dcterms="http://purl.org/dc/terms/"
   xmlns:oslc="http://open-services.net/ns/core#">
<oslc:ServiceProvider >
<dcterms:title1 rdf:parseType="Literal">AAA 1 &lt; 2 </dcterms:title1>
<dcterms:title2>BBB 1 &lt; 2 </dcterms:title2>
<dcterms:title3 rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#XMLLiteral">CCC 1 &lt; 2 </dcterms:title3>
</oslc:ServiceProvider>
</rdf:RDF>

And convert using jena to N3 (to avoid XML quotation):

        FileInputStream f = new FileInputStream("test2.xml");
        Model model = ModelFactory.createDefaultModel();
        RDFReader r = model.getReader();
        r.read(model, f, null);
        RDFWriter w = model.getWriter("N3");
        w.write(model,System.out,null);
It returns:

@prefix rdf:     <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix dcterms:  <http://purl.org/dc/terms/> .
@prefix oslc:    <http://open-services.net/ns/core#> .

[]    a       oslc:ServiceProvider ;
      dcterms:title1 "AAA 1 &lt; 2 "^^rdf:XMLLiteral ;
      dcterms:title2 "BBB 1 < 2 " ;
      dcterms:title3 "CCC 1 < 2 "^^rdf:XMLLiteral .

So to make long story short run your XMLLiteralTester against:
<dcterms:title rdf:parseType="Literal">1 < 2</dcterms:title>
which is equivalent to
<dcterms:title>1 &lt; 2</dcterms:title>
and you should get answer "Bad model".

